body:
I'm glad to see that the developers have been responsible and quick in fixing several issues, including [https://github.com/verilator/verilator/issues/5963](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/issues/5963).
However, during testing with the latest version of Verilator, I encountered another issue.
Below is the code that triggers the problem, `test.v`:

```verilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps
module out63_block
(
    input  wire        clock_4 ,
    input  wire        clock_8 ,
    output wire [28:5] out63
);

reg [28:0]  reg_12;
reg [28:22] reg_24;

wire        _0558_;
wire [28:0] _0670_;
wire [28:0] _0399_;
wire        _0085_;
wire [28:0] _0769_;
wire        _0305_;
wire [23:0] _0306_;

assign _0558_ = | reg_24[26:25]; // reg_24 = 0 or 1100110 ---> _0558_ == 0
assign _0670_ = _0558_ ? reg_12 : 29'h00000f93; // _0558_ == 0 ---> _0670_ == 29'h00000f93
assign _0399_ = - _0670_; // _0670_ == 29'h00000f93 ---> _0399_ = 29'b11111111111111111000001101101
assign _0085_ = ~ _0399_[2]; // _0399_[2] == 1 ---> _0085_ == 0
assign { _0769_[28:3], _0769_[1:0] } = { _0399_[28:3], _0399_[1:0] }; // _0769_ != 0
assign _0769_[2] = _0085_; 
assign _0305_ = ! _0769_; // _0769_ != 0 ---> _0305_ == 0
assign _0306_ = ! _0305_; // _0305_ == 0 ---> _0306_ == 1
assign out63  = _0306_; // out63 == 1

always @(posedge clock_4, posedge clock_8)
    if (clock_8) reg_12 <= 29'h00000066;
    else reg_12 <= { reg_12[28:27], 25'h0000001, reg_12[1:0] };

always @(posedge clock_4, posedge clock_8)
    if (clock_8) reg_24 <= 7'h66;
    else reg_24 <= reg_24;

endmodule
```

And the corresponding testbench `tb.v`:

```verilog
`timescale 1ns/1ps
module tb_out63_block;
    reg  clock_4;
    reg  clock_8;
    wire signed [28:5] out63;
    reg signed [7:0] tmp = -1;

    out63_block uut (
        .clock_4 (clock_4),
        .clock_8 (clock_8),
        .out63   (out63)
    );

    initial begin
        $display("tmp DEC: %d", tmp);
        $display("tmp BIN: %b", tmp);
        clock_4 = 0;
        clock_8 = 0;
        #2000;

        uut.reg_24 = 0;
        uut.reg_12 = 0;
        #2000;

        clock_4 = 0;
        clock_8 = 0;
        #10;
        $display("out63 DEC: %d", out63);
        $display("out63 BIN: %b", out63);

        #2000;
        clock_4 = 1;
        clock_8 = 1;
        #10;
        $display("out63 DEC: %d", out63);
        $display("out63 BIN: %b", out63);

        $finish;
    end

endmodule
```

You can reproduce the issue with the following commands:

```sh
verilator --binary -Wno-lint --timing   test.v tb.v
./obj_dir/Vtest
```

Verilator's output is:

```
tmp DEC:   -1
tmp BIN: 11111111
out63 DEC: -1
out63 BIN: 1
out63 DEC: -1
out63 BIN: 1
```

Icarus Verilog's output is:

```
tmp DEC:   -1
tmp BIN: 11111111
out63 DEC:        1
out63 BIN: 000000000000000000000001
out63 DEC:        1
out63 BIN: 000000000000000000000001
```

As you can see, there is an inconsistency in the output, and Verilator has two issues.

The first issue is: based on manual analysis (as noted in the comments in `test.v`), I believe the value of `out63` should be `1`, not `-1`. However, Verilator outputs `-1` when executing `$display("out63 DEC: %d", out63);`. But it seems the binary output from `$display("out63 BIN: %b", out63);` showing `1` is correct.

The second issue is: for some reason, Verilator does not display all the bits when printing `$display("out63 BIN: %b", out63);`, unlike `$display("tmp BIN: %b", tmp);`.

System details:

* Verilator version: Verilator 5.037 devel rev v5.036-32-g66e105b44 (mod)
* OS: Ubuntu 22.04.5 LTS (Jammy) Kernel/Release: 22.04

